  "local_port": 39964,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What do boxers say to each other when in the ring?",
  "response": "When boxers are in the ring, they may not always engage in a lot of talking, as their focus is primarily on the fight. However, some common phrases or expressions you might hear include:\n\n1. **Trash talk:** Boxers may use trash talk to try to \u043f\u0441\u0438\u0445\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438 destabilize their opponent. Phrases like \"You're going down,\" \"Is that all you've got?\" or \"You can't beat me\" are common.\n\n2. **Instructions from the corner:** Boxers often communicate with their coaches between rounds. The coach might say things like \"Keep your guard up,\" \"Move your feet,\" or \"Work the body.\"\n\n3. **Taunts and encouragement:** Some boxers might use short phrases to taunt or encourage themselves or their opponent. Phrases like \"Come on!\" or \"Let's go!\" are common.\n\n4. **Apologies or respect:** In some cases, if a boxer accidentally hits their opponent after the bell or in a way that was not intended, they might say \"Sorry\" or show respect by nodding or tapping gloves.\n\n5. **Technical talk:** Occasionally, boxers might discuss tactics or strategies during the fight, though this is less common. They might say things like \"Watch the jab\" or \"Stay on the outside.\"\n\nRemember, the intensity of a boxing match often limits conversation, and much of the communication happens non-verbally through body language and actions.",
